description:
Lines 400-410 in secretx-tpm2/src/lib.rs:

```rust
let validation = tss_esapi::structures::HashcheckTicket::try_from(
    tss_esapi::tss2_esys::TPMT_TK_HASHCHECK {
        tag: tss_esapi::constants::tss::TPM2_ST_HASHCHECK,
        hierarchy: tss_esapi::constants::tss::TPM2_RH_NULL,
        digest: tss_esapi::tss2_esys::TPM2B_DIGEST {
            size: 0,
            buffer: [0u8; 64],
        },
    },
)
.map_err(map_tpm_error)?;
```

This is a 10-line block of raw FFI struct construction for a concept that has a name: "null-hierarchy hashcheck ticket for externally-computed digests." The comments above explain the why, but the code block itself is visually heavy and the field-level intent is buried in the struct field names (`TPM2_ST_HASHCHECK`, `TPM2_RH_NULL`).

What goes wrong: On re-read, a developer must mentally parse 5 fully-qualified paths to understand this constructs a null ticket. If the tss-esapi API changes (e.g. adds a builder or a `HashcheckTicket::null()` constructor), this will be the last place updated because it looks like careful manual work.

Suggested fix: Extract a named helper:

```rust
fn null_hashcheck_ticket() -> Result<tss_esapi::structures::HashcheckTicket, SecretError> {
    tss_esapi::structures::HashcheckTicket::try_from(
        tss_esapi::tss2_esys::TPMT_TK_HASHCHECK {
            tag: tss_esapi::constants::tss::TPM2_ST_HASHCHECK,
            hierarchy: tss_esapi::constants::tss::TPM2_RH_NULL,
            digest: tss_esapi::tss2_esys::TPM2B_DIGEST {
                size: 0,
                buffer: [0u8; 64],
            },
        },
    )
    .map_err(map_tpm_error)
}
```

Then the call site becomes: `let validation = null_hashcheck_ticket()?;` — self-documenting.
